          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Which feature distinguishes lymphatic vessels from veins?</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which feature distinguishes lymphatic vessels from veins?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Lymphatic vessels contain one-way valves</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Both lymphatic vessels and veins contain valves to prevent backflow — the narration describes lymphatics as 'valved like veins.' This is a shared feature, not a distinguishing one.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Lymphatic vessels originate as blind-ended capillaries</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct! Lymphatic capillaries begin as blind-ended tubes in the tissues, collecting excess interstitial fluid. Blood capillaries, by contrast, connect arterioles to venules as part of a continuous circuit.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Lymphatic vessels carry fluid toward the heart</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Both lymphatic and venous systems return fluid toward the heart. Lymph drains into the venous system at the subclavian veins. This is a shared function, not a distinguishing feature.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Lymphatic vessels are accompanied by corresponding arteries</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Venae comitantes — paired veins running alongside arteries — are a feature of the deep venous system, not the lymphatic system.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Lymphatic capillaries begin as blind-ended tubes in the tissues, unlike blood capillaries which form part of a continuous arteriole–venule circuit. Both lymphatic vessels and veins have valves and return fluid toward the heart."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done! The blind-ended origin of lymphatic capillaries is their key structural distinction from blood vessels, allowing them to absorb excess tissue fluid."
                }
              ],
