          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>What is the defining structural feature of a portal system?</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>What is the defining structural feature of a portal system?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>An artery that branches into two separate capillary beds</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Portal systems are venous arrangements, not arterial. The portal vein lies between two capillary beds, carrying blood from one organ's capillaries to another's.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>A single capillary bed that drains into two different veins</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>A portal system has two capillary beds connected by a portal vein, not one capillary bed draining into two veins.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>A vein that connects two capillary beds</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct! A portal vein connects two capillary beds, allowing direct substance transport between organs — for example, the hepatic portal vein delivers absorbed nutrients from the gut to the liver for processing.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>A direct communication between an artery and a vein bypassing capillaries</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>That describes an arteriovenous anastomosis, which bypasses capillaries entirely. A portal system has two capillary beds connected by a vein — the opposite of bypassing exchange surfaces.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "A portal system is defined by a portal vein connecting two capillary beds. The hepatic portal system carries nutrients from the gut to the liver; the hypophyseal portal system delivers hypothalamic hormones to the anterior pituitary."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! Both the hepatic and hypophyseal portal systems follow this two-capillary-bed pattern, enabling direct delivery of substances between organs."
                }
              ],
